"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, it's Monday, and I'm gonna pitch my pile today. It's been about a week and a half since I set this thing up. The weather's gotten cold, but that won't affect the temperature of the pile at all. And so I'm gonna check this. Oh, it's flying up here. I'm gonna turn this so you can see it. Yeah, it's about 120. Almost 120. Check another spot. Maybe 115. Oh no, there it's 120. So it's gone down about 10 degrees since we last checked it, or 20 degrees since we last checked it, which is kind of indicative that we need to turn the pile, probably add some moisture. So today I'm gonna do both those things. The first thing I'm gonna do is aerate or uh water the pile a little bit. The outside's always the driest, of course, because that's what's drying out first. So I water that down just a little bit, and after that, I'm going to start to mix the pile, which is going to aerate it because that's really what's slowing it down, is that it uses up all the oxygen. The microbes uh breathe oxygen, they use it up in the pile. And so when you pitch it like this, you're aerating it. And of course, the first thing I'm gonna do is take off the outside layer of the uh the outside two or three inches of the pile and start the new pile with that. And then I'm gonna pile into this uh the meat of the pile and really get after it, and you'll see a little bit of steam coming off. I'll slow it down later so you can see it real proper. And I'm adding moisture as I go along. And here's a good version of that or picture that steam that I'm talking about. And you'll see that there's a white stuff that's coming off of this pile too. That's a fungus. And whenever your pile gets over about 120 degrees, you'll begin to see white uh fungus start to show up, and that will go away as soon as the pile cools down again. It's only there at the hottest points. And so I'm gonna pitch the whole thing, turn into a real nice pile. But if you see there's a lot of uh vegetable matter 